value.value: A structural quality inhering in the bearer by virtue of the bearer consisting of a single, maximally connected structure.

definition.value: What counts as maximally connected may be relative to some specification of granularity.

value.value: A structural quality inhering in the bearer by virtue of the bearer consisting of multiple structures lacking any physical connection to each other.
A quality of a single cell inhering in the bearer by virtue of the bearer's size or shape or structure.

definition.value: Use this term for morphologies that can *only* inhere in a cell, e.g. morphological qualities inhering in a cell by virtue of the presence, location or shape of one or more cell parts.

value.value: A quality inhering in a structure by virtue of it consisting of many of repeated, similar or identical subunits, arranged in some orderly array.

definition.value: A complete coverage of this domain would subclasses homopolymeric, copolymeric, crystalline.

value.value: A quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the extent to which the bearer is capable of being stretched or swollen.

definition.value: A quality of an object that has a value that is normal or average.
A coiling which is normal or average.
A contractility which is relatively normal or average.
A curvature which is relatively normal or average.
An elasticity which is relatively normal or average.
A flexibility which is relatively normal or average.
A life span which is relatively normal or average.
A mass which is relatively normal or average.
A size quality which is relatively normal or average
A viscosity which is relatively normal or average

value.value: A cell morphology that inheres in neurons which have a small round soma, a large number of short, smooth, or slightly beaded primary dendrites that give rise to only a few secondary branches, and a branched axon that establishes a dense axonal mesh with thin shafts.
A cell morphology that inheres in multipolar neurons with densely branched terminal axonal arborizations that form basket-like structures surrounding and synapsing to the somas of target cells.
A basket cell morphology that inheres in neurons with axonal arbors composed of frequent, short, curvy axonal branches that tend to be near their somata and within the same layer.

A basket cell morphology that inheres in neurons that are large, and typically ascend to give rise to many long horizontally and vertically projecting axon collaterals that traverse neighboring columns and can extend through all cortical layers.

A basket cell morphology that inheres in neurons which have simpler dendritic arbors (compared to small or large basket cell morphology), and an axonal plexus of intermediate density, composed of a few long, smooth axonal branches.

A cell morphology that inheres in neurons which have two principal dendrites that emerge from the soma and begin to branch some distance from it, have few spines, and branch in narrow fields. This is in contrast to bitufted morphology where branching occurs close to the soma.

definition.value: This is specific to cortical bipolar cells and are distinguished from retinal bipolar cell morphology which has an axon and dendrite emerging from opposite ends of the soma.

value.value: A cell morphology that inheres in neurons which are large and non-spiny, with dendrites radiating in a multipolar or bitufted pattern, often favouring the descending side, and axons that ascend directly from the superficial side of the soma, and travel upward without branching.
A Martinotti cell morphology that inheres in neurons which have axons that form a horizontal ramification, making it T-shaped.
A Martinotti cell morphology that inheres in neurons which have axons that form a fan-like plexus.
A cell morphology that inheres in neurons that have dendritic processes radiating from the cell body forming a star-like shape.

A cell morphology that inheres in neurons which are small and round, and make highly specialized synapses with the axon initial segments of pyramidal neurons, wrapping them with candle-shaped synaptic 'cartridges'.
Chandelier cells can be bitufted or multipolar.

A cell morphology that inheres in neurons which have two clusters of primary dendrites that originate directly and extend from opposite ends of the soma, and axons that form a plexus which spreads widely. Compared to the narrow vertical axonal projection of bipolar morphology, and the 'horse-tail' axonal cluster of double boquet cells, bitufted morphology has wide horizontal axonal spans, and branching that occur close to the soma. Their vertical projection is also less extensive and crosses mostly to neighboring layers.

A cell morphology that inheres in neurons which have spiny basal dendrites and resemble pyramidal cells but lose their apical dendrites as they mature. Their axons nearly always emerge from the descending side of the soma, but often recurve and ascend with arc-like collaterals.
A cell morphology that inheres in neurons which have a pyramidal shaped soma, a single axon, a large apical dendrite and multiple basal dendrites.
A pyramidal family morphology that inheres in neurons which have an apical tree which is oriented parallel to the pia.
A pyramidal family morphology that inheres in neurons which have a standard pyramidal shape with its apical dendrite aligned vertically.
A pyramidal cell morphology that inheres in neurons which have a distinct tuft formation, distal from the soma.
A pyramidal cell morphology that inheres in neurons which lack a clear tuft formation but extend to large radial distances.
A pyramidal cell morphology that inheres in neurons which lack a tuft formation but extend to small radial distances forming a star-like shape.
A pyramidal cell morphology that inheres in neurons which have an apical tree which is oriented towards the white matter.
A cell morphology that inheres in neurons with only one process, a neurite, that extends from the cell body. The neurite then branches to form dendritic and axonal processes.
A cell morphology that inheres in neurons which possess three or more neurites, usually a single axon and many dendrites and dendritic branches.
A cell morphology that inheres in neurons with dendrites that are bidirectional, emerging from opposite ends of the soma, with the two arbors extending in radial or tangential directions.

definition.value: This morphology type is distinct from bitufted cell morphology in that it refers to bitufted dendrite morphology rather than bitufted cell morphology.

value.value: A neuron projection quality that is a characteristic of neurons whose soma is located in the telencephalon and that project to structures outside the telencephalon
A neuron projection quality that is a characteristic of neurons with soma in the cerebral cortex and projections to the thalamus.
A neuron projection quality that is a characteristic of neurons with projections that terminate locally rather than distantly.
A neuron projection quality that is a characteristic of neurons that project to the medulla oblongata from other brain regions.
A physical quality inhering in a neuron by virtue of the relative location of its soma and the regions to which it projects and makes synaptic contacts in.
A neuron projection quality that is a characteristic of neurons with both soma and projections entirely within the telencephalon.

definition.value: A quality of continuant that exist at the anatomical level of organisation and anything under it. This includes, but is not limited to, cells , tissues, and components.
A quality inhering in an anotomical structure by virtue of its capacity to be stained by specific histological dyes.

value.value: An affinity inhering in an anatomical structure by virtue of the bearer exhibiting a molecular interaction that stains and colors, pale-pink, with Wright-Giemsa stain.
An affinity inhering in an anatomical structure by virtue of the bearer exhibiting a molecular interaction for both basic and acid stains under specific pH conditions.

label.value: quality of interaction of a substance with electromagnetic radiation

value.value: A quality of a substance on which or through which electromagnetic radiation impinges or traverses with respect to radiation. This substance quality changes the quality of the incident radiation with respect to any of: intensity, direction, scatter and wavelength.
A cell morphology that inheres in neurons with bitufted dendritic morphology but with the special feature of a tight fascicular axonal cylinder that resembles a 'horse tail'.
